<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-355-600  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 355 600.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  April 5 1990 n1208 p28(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Playing it safe with a system to trust. (investment companyMercury Ascot Management uses information technology to manageinvestments and customer service)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Vowler, Julia.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>UK investment company Mercury Ascot Management (MAM), subsidiaryof the merchant bank S.G.andP;  Warburg, invested heavily ininformation technology to improve its customer service, marketingand investment activities in a highly competitive market.andP;  MAMmanaged over 30 billion in 1989 investments, 70 percent of whichare pension funds.andP;  The firm's systems development manager, FrankParker, has the responsibility for the implementation of MAM's newsystem, which consists of an online real-time environment based onan IBM 3090 mainframe and new bank office, fund management, unittrust and customer accounts systems.andP;  Parker has about 95 staffworking on development of modules (each with 150 to 200 programs)of the Fundmaster bank office and fund management systems.andO;Paxus's client-driven Trust unit trust management system was alsoacquired.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Mercury Ascot Management (automation).andO;Topic:     Computer SystemsUpgradingInvestment BrokerageFinancial ServicesApplicationsPerformance Improvement.andO;Person:    Parker, Frank (management).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>